{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658394"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:47:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:47:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20744"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20744","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20744"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13620"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95825"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13620","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13620"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20744"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78604"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"11654"},{"type":"tags","id":"12441"},{"type":"tags","id":"12610"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32753"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32755"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95825","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95825"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA pathologist is examining tissue samples from several patients with suspected infections. One sample shows the following features:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMarked vascular congestion and increased permeability\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDense neutrophilic infiltration with nuclear fragmentation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAreas of liquefactive necrosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFormation of microabscesses\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFibrin deposition in vessel walls\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the predominant inflammatory pattern and likely causative organisms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Granulomatous inflammation caused by acid-fast bacilli","Suppurative inflammation caused by pyogenic bacteria","Fibrinous inflammation caused by viral pathogens","Chronic inflammation caused by parasitic infection","Caseous inflammation caused by fungal organisms"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuppurative inflammation caused by pyogenic bacteria\u003C/strong\u003E is characterized by intense neutrophilic infiltration leading to tissue destruction and abscess formation. The histological features described - including vascular changes, neutrophil accumulation, and liquefactive necrosis - are classic findings in suppurative inflammation caused by organisms such as \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranulomatous inflammation caused by acid-fast bacilli\u003C/strong\u003E shows epithelioid macrophages, giant cells, and lymphocytes rather than neutrophils\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibrinous inflammation caused by viral pathogens\u003C/strong\u003E primarily shows fibrin deposition without significant cellular infiltrate\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic inflammation caused by parasitic infection\u003C/strong\u003E typically shows eosinophils, lymphocytes, and plasma cells rather than neutrophils\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECaseous inflammation caused by fungal organisms\u003C/strong\u003E shows central necrosis with a granulomatous rim rather than liquefactive necrosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of microabscesses and liquefactive necrosis strongly suggests infection with pyogenic bacteria that release powerful chemotactic factors for neutrophils and tissue-destroying enzymes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Suppurative inflammation involves specific histological features including neutrophil infiltration, liquefactive necrosis, and vascular changes that distinguish it from other inflammatory patterns.","Different bacterial pathogens produce distinct patterns of tissue damage and inflammatory response based on their virulence factors.","The microscopic appearance and distribution of inflammatory cells helps distinguish between acute and chronic inflammatory processes."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; page 347."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78604"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20744"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78604"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-29T20:55:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T13:48:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13620"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95825"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11653"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Infectious diseases","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":7,"createdAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGr